[1] North Carolina - new rule
Date: Tue 18 Oct 2016
Source: Star News Online [edited]
http://www.starnewsonline.com/news/20161018/new-rule-relaxes-brunswicks-rabies-control-measures


New rule relaxes Brunswick's rabies control measures [Readers please note: This is only a rule in North Carolina. - Mod.TG]

Brunswick County Commissioners adopted a new rule for management of animals exposed to rabies.

A new rule relating to management of animals exposed to the rabies virus has been adopted by the county.

The rule change puts new exposure management control measures in place that shortens the amount of time exposed animals spend in quarantine.

The previous rule required euthanasia or a 6-month quarantine period for non-vaccinated dogs or cats, or dogs and cats that were overdue for a rabies vaccination, if they were exposed to the virus.

Though the option of euthanasia is continued under the new process, the adopted control measures call for a 4-month quarantine period versus a 6-month period. Additionally, exposed animals with overdue vaccinations with appropriate documentation could remain under at-home observations for 45 days.

"The proposed rabies control measures largely relaxes some of the existing standards that we have for rabies control in North Carolina," said David Stanley, Brunswick County's health and human services director.

Stanley said the rule change was proposed following the National Association of State Public Heath Veterinarians' 2016 Rabies Compendium, when new national guidance for post-exposure management control measures for dogs and cats was introduced.

The new measures continue to protect the public's health while using the most "current science" to deal with management of the virus, Stanley said.

[Byline: Makenzie Holland]

