[3] Michigan - bat, human exposure
Date: Thu 13 Oct 2016
Source: MLive [edited]
http://www.mlive.com/news/kalamazoo/index.ssf/2016/10/boy_awakens_to_rabid_bat_bitin.html


An 11-year-old Grand Junction [Michigan] boy and his brother are undergoing a series of preventative rabies shots after health officials confirmed that a bat that bit the older boy had rabies, a potentially deadly disease.

At 5 a.m. Monday [3 Oct 2016], Youth B felt something scratch his side as he slept, the child's mother said. When he [the child] reached down to brush it away, he was fully awakened by something biting his finger. He found a bat, still attached to his hand.

"Luckily he had the presence of mind to grab the animal," said the youth's mother. Unable to get out of his top bunk while clinging to the bat, he called to his brother, Youth J, 10, below to wake up and help him.

They hollered to their father, downstairs in the kitchen getting ready for work, and he awakened his wife.

Their mother said she knew that any bat bite required immediate medical attention, so they quickly woke up the younger children, 8 and 4 years old, and together the family went to South Haven Health System hospital's emergency room -- the bat, now dead, in tow.

"The nurses were scared of the bat," the mother said, but packed it for mailing into the lab to be tested. Youth B would need to have an immediate dose -- 2 shots in each arm -- of rabies immune globulin, they said, as a precaution to prevent the disease, which can be spread to humans through animal bites.

On Wednesday, when health officials confirmed the bat was, indeed, rabid, Youth J had to begin the same series of shots, in case he had been bitten in his sleep without noticing.

"The bite itself didn't look bad at all," the mother said, "and if the bat had not still been attached to his finger, my son might not know he had been bitten, they have such fine sharp teeth."

Nationwide, rabies commonly occurs in bats, skunks, fox, coyotes, raccoons, and a wide variety of other wildlife species, according to the Michigan Department of Health and Human Service [MDHHS].

Although human rabies cases are rare in the U.S., with an average of 2-3 cases documented each year, most of these cases in recent years have been caused by strains of rabies virus associated with bats, according to the health department. In the U.S., about 40 000 people each year receive treatment after rabies exposure, according to the MDHHS.

Animals that are submitted to the state health department for testing are those that have exposed a human being, a pet, or livestock, said MDHHS spokesperson Jennifer Eisner.

"The number of human cases of rabies has declined dramatically over the years thanks to development of improved human vaccines and the efforts to vaccinate pets and livestock against rabies," Eisner said. "In Michigan, the majority of rabies-positive animals are bats.

"If you find a bat in your home, especially it it's in a sleeping area, safely confine the animal and contact your local health department right away to find out if testing is recommended," she advised.

Erin Radke, public health nurse with the Allegan County Health Department, said fall is a common time for bats to get indoors as they seek warmth on cold nights.

Dr. Larry Wile, medical director for the Cass-VanBuren County Health Department, said repairing screens and patching any openings where bats may gain entrance is the 1st line of defense. If a bat does get inside, and bites someone, it's important to report the possible exposure and, if possible, to catch the animal for testing, he said.

Click here [http://www.cdc.gov/rabies/medical_care/index.html] to see the treatment recommended by the US Centers for Disease Control.

The prophylactic shots are very effective at preventing spread of the disease, and neither boy is very worried about catching rabies, the mother said.

The family has had bats get into their rural home from time to time during the 6 years they have lived there, the mother said. Usually, if the family cats didn't quickly catch them, the bats could be shooed back out again, the mother said. "We don't want to kill them," she said.

But the children are carefully checking their beds and bedrooms each night, she said.

According to the Michigan Department of Health and Human Services, in 2016, as of 10 Oct 2016, 33 bats and 4 skunks have tested positive for rabies in Michigan.

[Byline: Rosemary Parker]

