[5] New Jersey - raccoon, human exposure
Date: Fri 21 Oct 2016
Source: NJ.com [edited]
http://www.nj.com/burlington/index.ssf/2016/10/raccoon_killed_by_father_after_attacking_toddler_w.html


A raccoon that attacked a toddler before being killed by the child's father has tested positive for rabies, police said.

The 19-month-old was playing in a yard on Axe Factory Road [Mansfield, New Jersey] Wednesday [19 Oct 2016] when the raccoon attacked without provocation, police said in a statement.

The child's father fended off the raccoon with a pocket knife, killing it. The toddler was taken to the hospital for treatment and is recuperating at home.

Lab testing confirmed Friday [21 Oct 2016] the raccoon was rabid.

Police in Mansfield and neighboring towns are asking residents to report any wild animals that exhibit aggressive or unusual behavior.

Anyone who believes they had contact with a rabid animal should seek out medical testing and treatment.

[Byline: Cristina Rojas]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[It seems this father could have been exposed to saliva as well. Let us hope the authorities got a good description of this fight with the raccoon and accessed the dad as well.

These articles do not mention keeping your pets (dogs, cats, horses, cows, etc.) vaccinated against rabies. These bats or raccoons could just as easily have bitten a curious horse or show calf or an aged pet. These animals are then capable of exposing their human caregivers. So protect yourself and your pets by vaccinating against rabies.

Raising awareness in a community where such an event has occurred is important. The city/town/etc. in conjunction with veterinarians should be having rabies drive for pets and educating the public about this almost universally fatal disease. - Mod.TG

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=4578330,240.]
